    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The acidity caused by lactic acid buildup can indeed disrupt cellular functions, and there is a limit to how much the body can handle before it starts to break down.\n\nWhen the pH level in muscle cells drops below a certain threshold, it can activate various cellular pathways that help to mitigate the effects of the acidity. One such pathway is the bicarbonate buffering system, which works to neutralize the excess hydrogen ions (H+) by converting them into carbon dioxide (CO2) and water.\n\nHowever, if the acidity becomes too severe, it can lead to a condition known as \"metabolic acidosis.\" In this state, the body's ability to maintain proper pH levels is severely impaired, and cellular functions can become severely disrupted.\n\nTo give you a better idea, the normal pH range in muscle cells is around 7.2-7.4. When the pH drops below 7.0, it can start to cause problems, and when it drops below 6.8, it can lead to significant disruptions in cellular function.\n\nIt's worth noting that the human body is quite resilient, and it has various mechanisms to cope with metabolic acidosis. However, prolonged exposure to high levels of acidity can still lead to fatigue, muscle damage, and",
